data: # Lesson 22: Display temperature and humidity in a browser

## 1 Overview

In this lesson we are going to display in a browser the temperature and humidity, read using the DHT11 sensor.

## 3 Connections
Below you can find the schematic:
Also, you can find below a visual representation of the project:

## 4 Code

The code for this lesson is similar with the one provided for the previous
lesson because we are sending some data to the user that will be displayed in the web
page.

At the beginning of the code we will import the libraries used and set the
GPIO numbering in the **BCM** format. We will declare the type of the sensor used and
a variable that will store the pin used by this sensor. We will set this pin as an
OUTPUT.

Next, we have to deal with the routes for our user interface. For that, we need
a route to the default location, which is â/â. For this route we have created a function
that uses **template** to send the **index.html** page to the default location.

We have one more route attached to the **refresh** function where we will read
the temperature and humidity using an instruction from the adafruit library and the
result will be sent to the client in the JSON form

The code will end with a **run** call that will listen to HTTP requests on all
interfaces.

Now, let's talk about the HTML page. In the **head** we will include the link for
jQuery and in the **body** we will have a table with two rows and two columns. In the
first column you can find the name and in the second column you can find the value.

The JavaScript part has a **setInterval** instruction that will call the
**refreshFunction** every 1 s. In this function you can find the **getJSON** method that
will get some data from the server. Inside this method we will update the values in
the defined table from the HTML body, using the **.html** method.

"""
 * Credits: www.plusivo.com
 *
 * Lesson 22: Display temperature and humidity in a browser
 *
 * This lesson is created for the lesson "Display temperature
 * and humidity in a browser", where you will display the
 * humidity and temperature in a browser.
 *
 * More details can be found in the guide.
 *
 """

#import the libraries
from bottle import route, run, template, request
import RPi.GPIO as GPIO
import Adafruit_DHT

GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BCM)

#name the type of sensor used
type = Adafruit_DHT.DHT11

#declare the pin used by the sensor in GPIO form
dht11 = 25

#set the sensor as INPUT
GPIO.setup(dht11, GPIO.IN)

#define the route for the main page
@route('/')
def index():
    #at the '/' route we will return the index.html
    #template that is in the views folder
    return template('index.html')
@route('/refresh')
#define a function to send data to client
def refresh():
    #make the reading
    humidity, temperature = Adafruit_DHT.read(type, dht11)
    global buffer1
    global buffer2
    buffer1 = temperature
    buffer2 = humidity
    #we will send the new values if they are not null
    #else the previous readings will be send
    if humidity is not None and temperature is not None:
        #return the values to the client
        return {'temperature':temperature, 'humidity':humidity}
    else:
        #return the values to the client
        return {'temperature':buffer1, 'humidity':buffer2}

run(host = '0.0.0.0', port = '5000')
GPIO.cleanup()
